prompt: What is the time complexity of accessing an array element by index?
explanation: Array access by index is O(1) - constant time.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Binary Search?
explanation: Binary Search halves the search space each iteration.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Linear Search?
explanation: Linear Search must check each element in worst case.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Bubble Sort?
explanation: Bubble Sort uses nested loops comparing all pairs.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Merge Sort?
explanation: Merge Sort divides and merges in logarithmic levels.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Quick Sort (average case)?
explanation: Quick Sort averages O(n log n) with good pivots.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Quick Sort (worst case)?
explanation: Poor pivot selection leads to O(n²) worst case.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Insertion Sort (worst case)?
explanation: Worst case occurs with reverse-sorted input.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Selection Sort?
explanation: Selection Sort always performs n² comparisons.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Heap Sort?
explanation: Heap Sort maintains O(n log n) in all cases.

prompt: What is the time complexity of searching in a balanced BST?
explanation: Balanced trees maintain logarithmic height.

prompt: What is the time complexity of hash table lookup (average)?
explanation: Hash tables provide constant average lookup.

prompt: What is the time complexity of inserting at array start?
explanation: Must shift all existing elements.

prompt: What is the time complexity of stack push operation?
explanation: Stack operations are constant time.

prompt: What is the time complexity of queue enqueue?
explanation: Queue operations are constant time.

prompt: Which complexity represents constant time?
explanation: O(1) means time independent of input size.

prompt: Which complexity represents logarithmic growth?
explanation: O(log n) grows very slowly, typical of divide-and-conquer.

prompt: Which complexity represents linear growth?
explanation: O(n) means time proportional to input size.

prompt: Which complexity represents quadratic growth?
explanation: O(n²) often comes from nested loops.

prompt: Which complexity represents cubic growth?
explanation: O(n³) typically from three nested loops.

prompt: Which complexity represents exponential growth?
explanation: O(2ⁿ) doubles with each input increment.

prompt: Which complexity represents factorial growth?
explanation: O(n!) is the fastest growing common complexity.

prompt: Which grows faster: O(n) or O(n log n)?
explanation: O(n log n) grows faster than linear O(n).

prompt: Which grows faster: O(n²) or O(2ⁿ)?
explanation: Exponential always beats polynomial.

prompt: Which grows faster: O(2ⁿ) or O(n!)?
explanation: Factorial grows faster than exponential.

prompt: Which grows faster: O(log n) or O(n)?
explanation: Linear grows faster than logarithmic.

prompt: Which grows fastest among these?
explanation: Factorial is the fastest common complexity.

prompt: What is the complexity of Matrix Multiplication (naive)?
explanation: Three nested loops give cubic complexity.

prompt: What is the complexity of generating all subsets?
explanation: There are 2ⁿ possible subsets.

prompt: What is the complexity of generating all permutations?
explanation: There are n! possible permutations.

explanation: DFS visits each vertex and edge once.

prompt: What is the complexity of BFS graph traversal?
explanation: BFS visits each vertex and edge once.

explanation: Merge Sort requires additional O(n) space.

prompt: What is the space complexity of Quick Sort?
explanation: Quick Sort uses O(log n) stack space.

prompt: What is the space complexity of Heap Sort?
explanation: Heap Sort sorts in-place with O(1) space.

prompt: What is the space complexity of copying an array?
explanation: Need n space to store n elements.

prompt: Best complexity for searching sorted data?
explanation: Binary search on sorted data is O(log n).

prompt: Best complexity for general sorting?
explanation: Comparison sorts cannot beat O(n log n).

prompt: Complexity of checking if number is prime (trial division)?
explanation: Must check divisors up to sqrt(n).

prompt: Complexity of finding max in unsorted array?
explanation: Must examine all elements.

prompt: Complexity of palindrome check?
explanation: Must check all characters.

prompt: Complexity of reversing an array?
explanation: Must swap n/2 pairs of elements.

prompt: What is the space complexity of Heap Sort?
explanation: Heap Sort sorts in-place with O(1) space.

prompt: What is the space complexity of copying an array?
explanation: Need n space to store n elements.

prompt: Best complexity for searching sorted data?
explanation: Binary search on sorted data is O(log n).

prompt: Best complexity for general sorting?
explanation: Comparison sorts cannot beat O(n log n).

prompt: Complexity of checking if number is prime (trial division)?
explanation: Must check divisors up to sqrt(n).

prompt: Complexity of finding max in unsorted array?
explanation: Must examine all elements.

prompt: Complexity of palindrome check?
explanation: Must check all characters.

prompt: Complexity of reversing an array?
explanation: Must swap n/2 pairs of elements.

prompt: What is the time complexity of accessing an array element by index?
explanation: Array access by index is O(1) - constant time.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Binary Search?
explanation: Binary Search halves the search space each iteration.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Linear Search?
explanation: Linear Search must check each element in worst case.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Bubble Sort?
explanation: Bubble Sort uses nested loops comparing all pairs.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Merge Sort?
explanation: Merge Sort divides and merges in logarithmic levels.

prompt: What is the time complexity of Quick Sort (average case)?
explanation: Quick Sort averages O(n log n) with good pivots.
